      "properties": {"Node name for S&R": "Note"},
      "widgets_values": [
        "WAN 2.1 I2V SCENE RENDERER (FINAL QUALITY)\n=========================================\n\nUSE THIS WORKFLOW FOR: final renders after LTX prototyping confirmed the shot\nEXPECTED SPEED: ~12-15 min per 5s clip at 832x480 on 4090 mobile (16GB)\n\nWIDGET NOTES (WanImageToVideo):\n- [0] width = 832 (480p) or 1280 (720p — risky on 16GB)\n- [1] height = 480 (480p) or 720 (720p)\n- [2] length = 81 (frames, 1+80 generated, ~3.4s at 24fps) or 121 (~5s)\n- [3] steps = 30-40 for Q5 GGUF (lower = more motion artifacts)\n- [4] cfg = 5.0 (Wan likes higher CFG than LTX)\n- [5] scheduler = fixed (or 'flow shift' for more motion control)\n- [6] sampler = euler (or 'unipc' for slightly sharper)\n- [7] scheduler_sigma = simple\n- [8] sigma_shift = 1.0\n- [9] sigma_shift_end = 1.0\n- [10] motion_strength = 0.5 (0.1=static, 1.0=very dynamic)\n- [11] seed\n\n16GB VRAM TIPS:\n  • Use Q5_K_M or Q4_K_S GGUF quantization (Q8 will OOM at 832x480x81)\n  • Keep clip to fp8 (umt5_xxl_fp8.safetensors)\n  • If OOM: drop width to 704, or length to 49 (~2s), or use Q4_K_S\n  • Enable ComfyUI args: --lowvram --cache-none --use-pytorch-cross-attention\n\nWHY WAN OVER LTX FOR FINALS:\n  • Better photorealism (skin, eyes, hair detail)\n  • Better motion coherence (less warping on faces)\n  • Better prompt adherence\n  • ~30x slower than LTX → only use for locked shots"
      ],
